{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519319"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12992"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12992"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.17,0.09,0.01,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50205"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5429"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35477"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42835"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50205"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a sudden onset of right-sided weakness, difficulty speaking, and right-sided facial droop. She has a medical history of hypertension and a 20 pack-years of smoking. She has been prescribed perindopril to manage her hypertension however her husband states that she hasn\u0027t taken this in months and that she is on no other medications. On examination her GCS is 13, pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 160/100mmHg, SpO2 95% on air, temperature 36.8 \u00b0C and respiratory rate 16. She has 3/5 right upper and lower limb power and an obvious right-sided facial droop. A CT brain shows a moderate left-sided intracerebral haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step ?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous labetalol","Surgical evacuation","IV tranexamic acid","Platelet transfusion","IV mannitol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in this patient\u0027s management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eadministering intravenous labetalol. \u003C/strong\u003ECurrently, only rapid lowering of blood pressure in the acute phase of intracerebral hemorrhage (ICH) has been shown to reduce hematoma expansion and potentially improve outcomes for acute ICH. The Australian Stroke Living Guidelines recommend aiming for a systolic blood pressure of \u0026lt;140 mmHg in the acute setting. Acute lowering of SBP to \u0026lt;130 mm\u2009Hg in patients presenting with ICH and elevated BP is potentially harmful and should be avoided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical evacuation\u003C/strong\u003E is not the immediate step in managing patients with intracerebral haemorrhage unless the haemorrhage is causing life-threatening mass effect and the patient is deteriorating neurologically e.g. worsening GCS. This patient\u0027s presentation does not have any specific indications for immediate surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E may have a role in reducing haematoma growth as a antifibrinolytic drug, however further evidence from trials are required to change management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with more adverse outcomes unless the patient has severe thrombocytopaenia. There may be a role for platelet transfusion in reversing aspirin before a craniotomy however further studies are required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMannitol\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used to reduce intracranial pressure in conditions like traumatic brain injury. In the setting of haemorrhagic stroke, there is no clear evidence of benefit and therefore would not be the next appropriate best step.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In the acute management of intracerebral hemorrhage, rapid blood pressure control is crucial. Aim for a systolic blood pressure of \u003C140 mmHg using agents like labetalol."],"references":["Greenberg SM, Ziai WC, Cordonnier C, Dowlatshahi D, Francis B, Goldstein JN, Hemphill III JC, Johnson R, Keigher KM, Mack WJ, Mocco J. 2022 Guideline for the management of patients with spontaneous intracerebral hemorrhage: a guideline from the American Heart Association/American Stroke Association. Stroke. 2022 Jul;53(7):e282-361.","Hu W, Xin Y, Chen X, Song Z, He Z, Zhao Y. Tranexamic acid in cerebral hemorrhage: a meta-analysis and systematic review. CNS drugs. 2019 Apr 5;33:327-36.","Brogi E, Corbella D, Coccolini F, Gamberini E, Russo E, Agnoletti V, Forfori F. The role of platelet transfusions after intracranial hemorrhage in patients on antiplatelet agents: a systematic review and meta-analysis. World Neurosurgery. 2020 Sep 1;141:455-66.","Sprigg, N et al. Transexamic acide for hyperacute primary IntraCerebral Haemorrhage (TICH-2): an international randomised, placebo-controlled, phase 3 superiority trial. The Lancet. 2018 May 26; 391 (10135): 2107 - 2115. https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31033-X"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35477"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12992"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35477"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-08T16:00:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-08T16:00:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5429"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50205"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro